<font color="#FF0000">LOST INNOCENCE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep  6 20:12:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
When did it happen? When did we lose our innocence? When did we come of age. When were our eyes opened, are hearts darkened and life had a meaning?<br><br>
In order to gain experience we need to loose our innocence. In that lost we begin to understand what life is really all about. <br><br>
The day I began to experience and to value life was the day I boarded the six bi-truck enroute from Dan Nang to Hill 37. Where the 3rd Marine Battalion 7th Marine Regiment was located. From Dreams of Glory, clear fields of Fire, © Copyright 1967 Cook Barela<br><br>
 LOST INNOCENCE<br>
Eroute to Battalion Headquarters<br>
DaNang, South Viet Nam<br>
1300 Hours, Sunday June 18th, 1967<br>
About two miles out we entered a Marine compound and stopped near a small command post where we loaded on board six cases of soda and ten cases of beer. A Marine corporal with the battalions mail bag joined us and took the right front shotgun riding position in the truck. <br>
Two other Marines jumped into the back of the truck with us. One was short and a boot like us, I could tell by the cotton utilities he wore and his clean leather boots.  He was however, carrying a fully loaded M16 rifle. The other Marine was an old salt.  He wore the new type of light weight utilities, was tall, skinny, and had a dark tan. We were hot wearing our heavy cloth utilities, the old salt looked cool in his. His eyes were distant as if he was seeing something that we couldn't see. <br>
We were sitting with our backs against the cab to avoid the dust, he sat near the tail end where he could watch where we were going. I sat silently studying and staring at the Marine. He held his M14 rifle close, close to his body and ready.  It was evident that he was fully alert and aware of his surroundings. His expressionless eyes revealed much, they were constantly skimming the roadway ahead. Like a vigilant hawk, he barely moved his head all while expertly scanning the terrain for any signs of the enemy.  His eyes were constantly shifting positions, checking out tree lines and the numerous hedgerows and clusters of thick bushes that grew alongside the roadway. Each glimpse seemed to bring back memories of similar settings and ambushes.  When this happened his blank stare would return, as if he was viewing images in the back of his mind and for those split seconds he was gone. Then, almost immediately he was back, his eyes once again focused on the terrain before us. Then his eyes would began once again their shifting sequence, scanning and reconnoitering the terrain up ahead.  To him it was a habit, a need and I became fascinated by him, studied his movements, his facial wrinkles, his torn, dirty and worn out fatigues, then all of a sudden his head shifted, his eyes opened wide but his hands never moved toward his weapon. <br>
I knew something was up, he was looking to his left, toward my right rear, sucking in and analyzing images from something that was happening up in the air, something ahead of us. I turned quickly to my right to see what he was looking at. The other Marines unaware of his interest were lost in their own secert thoughts. <br>
Up in the air, no more then thirty-forty-fifty feet away a fierce air battle was being waged by two birds. The larger of the two, a skinny black bird had something in his beak and the smaller white bird was attacking, squealing, screaming and pecking away at the larger birds head. Dive bombing him while the larger bird turned, twisted and tried to maneuver out of his way. <br>
As the truck passed by the commotion, another smaller long white tail bird joined in the attack and the skinny black bird dropped his pray. The small featherless plump baby bird plundered to its death. The birds continued their assault, relentlessly pursuing the larger bird as it tried frantically to get away. <br>
I caught the eyes of the short timer just then and he looked into mine. He realized that I had also witnessed the aerial conflict. But it was in his eyes that for the first time I caught the glimpse of the after images embedded deep within, in his heart and mind. I saw the pain and the suffering associated with the struggles of life that dwelled there and a sense of acknowledgment flowed between us and for a split second I shared all his pain, suffering, shame, guilt and the same battle scenes he had witnessed and also the strength he had found to endure. I learned more about war in that micro-second of life then in all my training. I had heard stories of war now, I was beginning to understand what it all meant.<br>

<p><code>-- Suicide India, USMC 1st Marine Division  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


